title: For Trade:  AR 15 Flat Top Rare!, High Quality Precision Shooter!
postcontent:
Eagle Arms "Action Master" .223/5.56 rifle produced in 1993, Retail 1993 was $1075.
Factory original , unaltered rifle...20” Douglas stainless steel 1:9” twist match bbl float tube, flat top upper receiver and Natl match trigger.

Eagle Arms, back then was basically the retail outlet for Lewis Machine & Tool's AR's, which are widely regarded as some of the best. 
Here is a short article about Eagle Arms:
Karl Lewis and Jim Glazier formed a company named Eagle Arms in Coal Valley Illinois
in 1986. Lewis had manufactured a wide variety of both commercial and military parts for M16 rifles, and Eagle
Arms assumed the increasingly distracting retail business from Lewis’ company, Lewis Machine and Tool (LMT).
Eagle Arms initially marketed M16 and AR15 type rifle parts. The early Stoner patents had expired, and Eagle was able to build both parts and complete rifles. In 1989 Eagle commenced production of complete rifles, with LMT serving as the major supplier.
In January 1994 Mr. Mark Westrom purchased the company. 
After the purchase, he continued producing Eagle Arms EA15 rifles with a focus on high grade target rifles. The bulk of the engineering work was contracted out to Lewis Macine Tool.
 In early 1995 Westrom purchased those rights, and production of ArmaLite rifles resumed in Illinois. The corporation was reorganized as ArmaLite, with Eagle Arms
converted to a division of ArmaLite. First shipments of new ArmaLite rifles began in 1995.

I contacted Armalite and furnished serial number and photos of this rifle....
****  Here is the reply from them..."Your rifle is an Action Master rifle produced in 1993, 20” Douglas stainless steel 1:9” twist match bbl float tube, flat top upper receiver and Natl match trigger.

So this is basically a 'Pre-ban' rifle that was made by LMT (Lewis Machine Tool)....If you do not know who they are....search online and you will find the quality and prices of their guns.

I got this from the original owner ...he bought it new and it has ~500 rounds thru it.

See the reviews on this same "Action Master" series of rifles in the 1992 American Rifleman Magazine Photos..... copy the link below into your browser and go to see more pics!!>>>>>>>>>>

https://plus.google.com/photos/REDACTEDREDACTED7/albums/REDACTED764580977


I am retired and my hobby is collecting and trading guns; as such, I would prefer to trade this rather than sell it.

This is not some mix and match AR that someone tossed together!! Look at the link pictures and see what others say online about the quality of LMT and specifically this Action Master from Eagle Arms!!

I will be open to trades where cash comes my way....if both parties feel it is fair.

The Modular Sleep System (MSS) is a modular sleeping bag used by the United States armed forces. These are genuine USGI obtained from a government auction.

The MSS consists of a camouflaged, waterproof, breathable Gore-Tex bivy cover, a lightweight patrol sleeping bag, and an intermediate cold weather sleeping bag. Compression sacks are included to store and carry the system.


The patrol bag provides cold weather protection from 35 to 50 degrees Fahrenheit. The intermediate bag provides cold weather protection from minus 5 to 35 degrees Fahrenheit. Together, the patrol bag and intermediate bags provide extreme cold weather protection in temperatures as low as minus 30 degrees Fahrenheit. The bivy cover can be used with each of three MSS configurations (patrol, intermediate, or combined) to be comparable with the environment in which the system is being used; the bivy cover provides environmental protection from wind and water.

For sale: Selling my baby..., a 2009 Bowtech Sentinel compound bow. This bow is the one with the Roller Guard, not the FlxGuard. Right-handed, 50-60 lbs., 7" brace height, 36.75" axle-to-axle (I think), draw lenght is 30.5-24.5", 80% let-off, supposed to be about 330 fps IBO (I never shot close to IBO, so I never got close to that speed). Buying a new bow...

String is a white/blue twist, one cable is white, and one is blue. The strings and cables are less than one year old and are in excellent shape (MINIMAL serving spread around tight bends on cams), they were custom built by Stone Mountain, and they are the Titanium Pre-Stretched line. String has a 3/16" blue G5 Meta peep (face has been blacked with a sharpie to provide a more definitive "halo" for the eye. The string loop is a white 4.25" PSE, with a small serving of red material above the top knot to provide a reference point in case of necessary replacement of loop, the loop is in good shape yet, it was only shot with a Carter RX1 release. The kisser button is a double clamp Bohning Hunter hard plastic one. There are no silencers on the string, but each control cable has one oem Bowtech silencer on it (replaced when I replaced the string). The rubber string stop was also replaced when the string was.

Bow limbs are not original camo, as they have been replaced with 50-60 lb. limbs about a week ago, they are black. The limb texture is also the new one, the riser is the InVelvet finish in Realtree Hardwoods Green. The camo riser and black limbs give it a sharp look though... The SVL split limb silencers are included.

Bow will include a Ripcord Code Red drop-away rest that is less than one year old. The rest does not have the top containment bar on it, due to the Roller Guard/rest placement. The Ripcord's drop cord has been served into the one control cable to reduce weight and for more security. The bow also will include the Octane 7" hydraulic stabilizer in matching camo. Front of the handle has the SVL handle strip.

The bow is used, but as stated, it was my baby . This bow was used for hunting and target. Cams show minor dings/rubs/marks. Does show minor wear, and some of the screws show minimal dustings of rust and slight use wear in allen key insets... For a 2009 this is in EXCELLENT shape!

This bow would make a great target or hunting bow, when I had my sight on it, I had it dialed out to 90 yds. WHEN I did my part, this bow would shoot between 4-6" @ 90 yds. I had to be careful at the ranges of 40 yds. and under due to the fact that the arrows would touch.

Bow is set at 60 lbs., and a 28.5" draw right now.

I would like to get $500 shipped in continental US, $475 cash FTF. Any questions, feel free to ask before you commit. Reasonable offers will be entertained if it doesn't sell soon. I may list elsewhere also though...

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Endotactical Glock Stock Adapters - put a AR15 stock on your glock!
postcontent:
(all NFA rules apply. the fast and legal way to enjoy this is to also get a 16" barrel and convert your glock to a carbine. or, register it as a Short Barreled Rifle and pay the $200 tax. If you just slap this on your glock, you will be breaking the law. Not that anyone would know or care- just giving the facts here.)

1.Can I use ANY stock assembly with the tactical stock adapter? 
Yes.  You can use any fixed stock, collapsible stock, folding stock etc.  If it fits on AR-15 / M16 / M4 rifles it will work with the tactical stock adapter. 



2.What are all the parts I need in order to use the tactical stock adapter?
1) Buffer tube (also known as a "receiver extension")
 2) The shoulder stock of your choice
 3) Anti-rotational receiver plate (should be included when you buy most stock assemblies)
 4) Castle nut (should be included when you buy most stock assemblies)


ENDO Tactical - What parts you need 



3.Do I need to insert the buffer spring and the buffer weight inside the receiver extension (buffer tube) before I attach it to the tactical stock adapter?
No.  Neither will be useful in this instance. 



4.What tools do I need in order to install a tactical stock adapter?
None, but you may want to use a special AR-15 / M16 / M4 stock wrench to snug the castle nut up against the reciever plate, which holds your buffer tube secure.  The castle nut does not need to be very tight so a good hand tightening should work fine. A dot of blue loctite will stop the castle nut from coming loose if the issue ever arises. 



5.Can my compensated (C), long (L), or Rough Textured Frame (RTF) version Glock be used with the tactical stock adapter? 
Yes, it will work with models G17C, G17L, G20C, G21C, G21L, G22C, G24C, and G31C and RTF versions, because the frame is the same size. 



6.Will it fit the new Gen4 Glocks? 
Yes, with very minor modification to the backstrap insert of the adapter.

title: For Trade:  HK MP5A5 Heckler & Koch
postcontent:
Heckler & Koch HK MP5A5 22LR
This is the HK MP5 22 made by Carl Walther under license from HK, it is currently the only licensed HK trainer. It is made in Germany and imported by Umarex. It is almost identical in weight and function with the MP5N 9mm, intended as a low cost trainer. It IS NOT the cheap plastic GSG clone, it a metal receiver fully licensed replica/trainer and will accept most all standard HK sight rails, forgrips and other accessories.

Specs (copied directly from Walther Arms)
Caliber:	.22 Long Rifle
Mag Capacity:	10, 25 rnds
Weight w/out Mag:	5.9 lbs
Overall Length:	26.8–33.8 in
Barrel Length:	16.1 in
Barrel Twist:	1 in 13-3/4 in
Grooves:	6
Operation:	Blowback
Front Sight:	Interchangeable Posts
Rear Sight:	Adjustable Wind & Elevation

I've had a blast with this rifle. It's pure joy to shoot with excellent accuracy with iron sights and will accept all MP5 sight rails and accessories. Mine has a Blackhawk single point mash hook sling and one extra magazine (so a total of 2), factory included small tools and additional front sight post, the original box and paperwork.

It does have some finish damage around the rear sling point. The mash hook is a little harder on a weapon but it is a positive connection sling point, so you can rest assured your weapon isn't going to fall off as you run through a shooting stage. (see photos) Otherwise, the fit and finish are excellent.

Face to face trade, must be willing to complete a bill of sale for private party transaction, have a valid photo ID.

Thanks

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Remington 11-96 12ga Euro Lightweight & Optional Stock
postcontent:
Up for sale is a very rare shotgun. This is a Remington 11-96, which was manufactured from 1996-99 and was voted the shotgun of the year in 1997. Essentially this is an upgraded 11-87 that has been lightened with the addition of a trimmed receiver, and a different contour barrel and forearm. What really sets this one apart is the Claro Walnut factory adjustable stock which was nearly a $400 option. This was the first/only time that Remington offered an adjustable stock on the 1100 series, and I have only seen photos of 3 with this option! You will also find that the scroll work on the receiver is a notch above the typical work you see, and combined with the stock gives it an excellent eye appeal. That means you will get looks and compliments from others on the hunt or at the range, make sure you can handle that. 

Because of the weight, this shotgun points exceptionally fast. Weighing in around 7 pounds also makes it easy to carry in the field without sore arms at the end of the day. You would think that with the lighter weight it would punish your shoulder, but that is not the case. It has proved effective with skeet and trap, and is very quick to the bird. It is in excellent condition, with very few shells fired (estimated in the 200 range). It will come with a nice Bulldog case and additional gas seals. If you have any questions please let me know.
